# Four long sentences

This approach demonstrates poor writing practice because it deliberately expands simple ideas into unnecessarily long sentences that reduce clarity, making it harder for readers to quickly understand what is being communicated.
By forcing each sentence to exceed twenty-five words, the structure becomes overly complex and inefficient, which contradicts guidance on clear communication and risks frustrating users who need concise and accessible content.
The insistence on avoiding shorter sentences removes flexibility for writers, discouraging them from making natural improvements such as splitting ideas into clearer parts or simplifying phrasing where appropriate.
Overall, this style encourages verbosity and over-complication, suggesting a misunderstanding of good content design principles, where the goal should instead be readability, clarity, and ease of comprehension for the audience.